'''Aboulomania''' ({{etymology|gre|a–|without||boulē|will}})<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|title=aboulia|encyclopedia=The New Oxford American Dictionary|edition=2nd}}</ref> is a [[mental disorder]] in which the patient displays [[pathological]] indecisiveness.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://phrontistery.info/mania.html|title=Manias and Obsessions|year=2007|work=The Phronistery|first=Stephen|last=Chrisomalis}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|isbn=9788131903537|last=Rawat|first=P.S.|title=Midline Medical History|publisher=Jane Publishers|year=2002|page=11}}</ref> It is typically associated with [[anxiety]], [[Chronic stress|stress]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]], and mental anguish, and can severely affect one's ability to [[social functioning|function socially]]. Although many people suffer from indecision, it is rarely to the extent of obsession.<ref name="JenniferByrne">{{cite  web|url=http://www.livestrong.com/article/181144-how-to-overcome-indecision/|first=Jennifer Byrne|last=2010|title=How to Overcome Indecision|work=Livestrong}}</ref> The part of the brain that is tied to making rational choices, the [[prefrontal cortex]], can hold several pieces of information at any given time.<ref name="JenniferByrne" /> This may quickly overwhelm somebody when trying to make decisions, regardless of the importance of that decision. They come up with reasons that their decisions will turn out badly, causing them to over-analyze every situation critically in a classic case of [[paralysis by analysis]]. Lack of information, valuation difficulty, and outcome uncertainty can become an [[obsession (psychology)|obsession]].<ref>{{cite journal|last=Rassin|first=Eric|title=A psychological theory of indecisiveness|journal=Netherlands Journal of Psychology|volume=63|issue=1|pages=1–11|doi=10.1007/BF03061056}}</ref>

